<p>As Shakouri points out, CPCs are more likely to have negative impacts on members of these communities through their false promises. ‚ÄúFake clinics are trying to put a soft face to the anti-abortion movement and also to position itself as a solution,‚Äù she said.</p>

<p>‚ÄúOne of the largest critiques that anti-abortion folks get is √îOkay, if you ban abortion, how are you going to take care of these pregnant people and their subsequent children?‚Äô and we know CPCs exist to talk people out of an abortion, but the support that they promised afterward, including free diapers, parenting classes, all this support, it either doesn‚Äôt materialize or it times out or it‚Äôs just not sufficient a person carrying an unintended pregnancy to term,‚Äù said Shakouri. ‚ÄúOne box of diapers is not going to help someone who is facing poverty and doesn‚Äôt have childcare solutions, so we know that fake clinics are not a solution to the post-<em>Roe</em> world.‚Äù</p>

